      "newValue": "**Summary of Guideline for Carbetocin Use in Caesarean Birth:** Carbetocin is recommended to prevent postpartum hemorrhage (PPH) during caesarean birth, replacing oxytocin (not used together). **Administration:** - Give **100 mcg IV over 1 minute** after baby’s birth and cord clamping. - Consider dose reduction in low-risk elective cases. - Never give before birth or exceed 100 mcg. **Roles:** - **Anaesthetist:** Prepares, administers, documents. - **Obstetrician/Midwife:** Monitors uterine tone, lochia, escalates concerns. - **Theatre team:** Maintains stock. **Contraindications:** - Pregnancy/labour prior to birth. - Hypersensitivity to carbetocin/oxytocin. - Serious cardiovascular disease, severe pre-eclampsia/eclampsia. **Cautions:** - Cardiovascular disease, hypotension, hyponatraemia, pre-eclampsia, general anaesthesia. **Adverse Effects:** - Nausea, headache, hypotension, flushing, chest pain, dyspnea. **Training/Monitoring:** - Follow BNF, SPC, NHS Injectable Medicines Guide. - Audit compliance and incident reviews. *References: BNF, SPC carbetocin.*",
